@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@
+"""
+    dotu(a::AbstractVector, b::AbstractVector)
+
+A function that computes the non conjugate dot product between two vectors. It is equivalent
+    to calling `dot(conj(a), b)`.
+
+# Arguments
+- `a::AbstractArray`, a vector being dot producted (is labeled as a array to allow for 
+    views).
+- `b::AbstractArray`, a vector being dot producted (is labeled as a array to allow for 
+    views).
+# Returns
+- A scalar that is the non-conjugated dot product between two vectors.
+"""
comment.body: I agree that abstract vector may be a better choice in an ideal world. Changing the inputs has been more complicated than I would have hoped. The reason for these difficulties is that for a matrix `A`, a `view(A, 1, :)` is a different type than `view(A,1:row_s, :)`. The logical thing would be to set the compressed_mat type to be the union of these two possibilities, and having `compressed_mat` be defined based on the whether `row_s == 1`. When I tried this the tests still failed. So, considering that the dot function works with both types of views, the best option is leaving it as it was originally and possibly renaming it if we are still concerned about the `dot` being applied to abstract arrays here.
